{"key":"processedPost-10129101","value":{"id":10129101,"first":10128854,"last":10134381,"when":1239208086,"utime":"04/08/09 07:28 PM","content":"The same way.&nbsp; Bring your substrate or casing layer material to field capacity and load into plastic bags or jars.&nbsp; Put in a pot of water and heat to boiling, while watching a meat thermometer in the center of the bag or jar.&nbsp; When the temp reaches 140F, shut off the stove or reduce to lowest setting.&nbsp; Check every few minutes and adjust the stove burner as necessary to keep the center of your substrate between 140F and 160F for one hour.<br />No, I wasn't being sarcastic.&nbsp; I just hate the idea of leaching the good stuff from manure by squeezing it out after over-hydration.&nbsp; It's also much faster this way, since there's no draining or squeezing involved.<br />RR","title":"Re: How to make a substrate draining Press and pasteurize (FULL TEK)"}}